A unique way to travel between states! Have you ever been on the @ssbadgerferry? 

Location: Manitowoc, WI to Ludington, MI
Available: Seasonal, May-October
Crossing Time: 4 hours

Travel Tips:
- If you know that you get motion sickness, take dramamine about an hour before. They also have motion sickness bracelets and ginger ale available.
- If it’s nice out, the outside lounge chairs at the bow of the ship are the best spots. You’ll be in the sun, you’re protected from the wind, and it seemed like the least rocky part of the ship.
- You cannot access your vehicle once you’re onboard.

I really enjoyed taking the ferry! It was a cool addition to our Michigan adventure! #puremichigan

Details ⬇️

1. Sail Door County: Choose between The Passage North (6 passenger) or The Edith Becker (22 passenger, pictured). (~$45+/person)
2. The tulip fields at Richardson’s Adventure Farm: Absolutely beautiful! We went in mid-May 2022. (~$12-15/person)
3. Sleeping Bear Sand Dunes: So many cool places to explore. Plus, Traverse City is an awesome town!
4. Kayak the Apostle Islands: If you get good weather, 10/10 experience. We went with Lost Creek Adventures (~$85/person)
5. Rent dune buggies: SunBuggy Silver Lake in Mears, Michigan
6. SS Badger Ferry: A fun and different way to travel between states! Manitowoc, WI to Ludington, MI
7. Go on a canoe trip: For an epic trip, go to the Boundary Waters in Minnesota. For a less intense trip, check out the Willow Flowage in northern Wisconsin.

This lovely hiking spot in northwest Wisconsin features a stunning overlook and a 70-foot high waterfall.

📍St. Peter’s Dome Recreation Area

What is it? 
An outdoor area with two popular trails - one leading to Morgan Falls and the other to a scenic overlook at the top of St. Peter’s Dome.

Where is it? 
Marengo, WI (northwest Wisconsin)

What does it cost?
There’s a $5 day use pass

What Should I Know?
- Trail to St. Peter’s Dome: Approximately 3.6-mile round-trip hike, fairly rugged with quite a bit of exposed rock and steep climbs. 
- Trail to Morgan Falls: Accessible trail with boardwalk and bridge that is nearly .75 miles one-way.
- On a clear day you can see Lake Superior and the Apostle Islands over 20 miles to the north. 
- Also referred to as “Old Baldy”
- A vault toilet is located in the parking area
- Bring bug spray! There were a lot of mosquitoes when we were here in June.

📍Sundara Inn & Spa, Wisconsin Dells, WI

What is it?
A year-round, adults-only luxury spa tucked in the woods with pools, spa services, on-site dining and beautiful rooms & suites. You can either go for the day or nightly.

Disclaimer: Sundara is electronics-free in all common areas. Prior arrangements were made so I could capture these images.

What Should You Know?
- You’ll be provided with a robe and sandals that you’ll wear the whole time! This is the least I’ve ever packed on a trip. For an overnight stay, a swimsuit, pjs, and 1-2 comfy outfits for under the robe will do (keep in mind, the robes are long and heavy and will keep you warm)
- The outdoor infinity pool and the indoor/outdoor pool w/ the swim-up bar are both heated and are open year-round.
- We stayed in one of the new Vanya Reserve suites which featured a private hot tub, feather bed, wet bar, and a rain shower. 
- There’s an on-site restaurant! Remember, you’ll wear your robe to eat so no need to change :) All three meals I had were delicious.
- They offer complimentary wellness classes such as yoga, meditation, culinary demonstrations, skincare education, and more.

📍Door Bluff Headlands County Park, Ellison Bay, Wisconsin

What is it? 
The largest county park in Door County with natural hiking trails. This park is undeveloped except for an access road to its interior. 

What does it cost?
Free

What Should You Know?
- Be very, very careful! The unofficial trail to the overlook is full of roots and follows the cliffs edge which is a straight drop to the water. You can walk more towards the interior so you’re not right by the edge.
- It’s an unmarked trail but you should be able to see where others have walked. If you follow the waters edge (on your right), after about 10-15 minutes, you basically run right into the overlook spot. There’s a bench there too!

📍Big Sable Point Lighthouse, Ludington, MI (lower MI, west coast)

What Is It?
A beautiful lighthouse that you can tour located within Ludington State Park. Situated on Lake Michigan and surrounded by a sprawling sand beach, this lighthouse is a must-see! 

What Should You Know?
- You’ll need a Michigan Recreation Passport (state park sticker) to enter the park. 
- You’ll walk 1.8 miles (one way) along a sandy trail to reach the lighthouse. 
- There are restrooms next to the main building.
- Don’t forget to bring money! If you want to walk to the top, it’s $8 per adult and $5 per child (as of 2021 when I visited). They also have a cute gift shop!
- You can volunteer to become a Resident Keeper and live here for up to 2 weeks! Volunteers must be 18 years or older and duties include:  cleaning, tower tours, historical interpretation, welcoming guests, taking admissions, gift shop/cash register, light maintenance duties, stocking, and grounds work. Visit splka.org to learn more.

📍Briq’s Soft Serve | Central & Northern Wisconsin

What is it?
An iconic Wausau soft serve ice cream spot with 7 locations (Wausau, Wausau River Life, Weston, Rib Mountain, Mosinee, Minocqua, Rhinelander)

How to get inducted into the “One Hundred Pound Club”: 
- Order the Briq’s large cone (aka “the pounder”)
- Take as long as you need to collect 100 Pound Club Cards (don’t forget to ask for them when you order!) 
- Once you reach 100, bring your cards to any of the 7 locations and ask for a manager. You’ll provide them with your contact info so you can get on their mailing list.
- Now you’re officially into the club which means you’re rewarded with free, all-you-can eat ice cream for two days every year for the REST OF YOUR LIFE 

What else should you know?
- The 2 free days are predetermined by the Briq’s ownership team each year - I believe you’re made aware of these days via mail
- Cones come in vanilla, chocolate, or zebra
- Their soft serve is 96% fat free

📍Bittersweet Lakes State Natural Area | St. Germain, WI (northern)

What is it?
A series of four small lakes, Prong, Bittersweet, Smith & Oberlin, with four short portages in between and with five primitive, reservable campsites.

What should you know?
- If you paddle all four, you’ll go south to north, from Prong to Bittersweet to Smith to Oberlin
- If you want, you could drive to Bittersweet and launch from there instead of Prong
- Keep in mind, these lakes are very small! It doesn’t take long to paddle from one side to the other. Bittersweet is the largest at 104 acres. 
- These are no-motor lakes
- No state park sticker needed
- Bring bug spray! 
- To reserve a campsite, go to wisconsin.goingtocamp.com. Select ‘boat-in’, ‘Northern Highland-American Legion’ park, ‘tent’. Click ‘south campgrounds’, then ‘Bittersweet Wild Lakes’.

My experience:
We parked by Prong Lake (the first lake) by the yellow gate on the right. This was the longest portage - it probably took about 10 minutes to carry our kayaks/canoe down the wooded path to the lake. If I visit again, I’ll probably skip this portage and just launch at Bittersweet. The mosquitoes were pretty bad in the woods but once we were on the lake, it was totally fine! We took our time paddling along the perimeter of each lake, enjoying the sunshine and relaxing on the water. We spent about 4 hours here.

- Two authentic Finnish breakfast spots! I loved the Finnish French Toast at Suomi’s which was walking distance from The Vault Hotel. At Nisu Cafe, make sure to try the Pannukakku with raspberry jam & whipped cream!

Lunch: Four Suns Fish & Chips
- The cutest little fast-casual restaurant with fresh caught fish from Lake Superior. I ordered one of their whitefish tacos which was so tasty! 

Dinner: @theambassadorhoughton
- This place was hoppin’! Located in a historic building with curved architecture, The Ambassador is a popular place and known for their pizzas! It was walking distance from our hotel which was a plus.

Tour: @quincymine
- If you like history, definitely check out the Quincy Mine. We did the full tour which, from start to finish, lasted about two hours and 15 minutes. Make sure to dress WARM. I’d highly recommend layers and a warm jacket and waterproof shoes.

Hike: Estivant Pines Wilderness Nature Sanctuary & Nara Nature Park
- Estivant is outside of Copper Harbor, a little off the beaten path but a lovely place for a hike. You’ll walk past 300-500 year old white pines!
- Nara Nature Park is located in Houghton near the Michigan Tech campus.

Sightsee: Brockway Mountain Drive & Eagle Harbor Lighthouse
- Brockway Mountain is an absolute must in the fall! There’s no hiking required here, you simply drive right up to the large overlook. 
- Eagle Harbor Lighthouse is a charming red brick lighthouse that’s still in operation today.

Sunset: Calumet Waterworks Park & McLain State Park
- These are both great places to watch the sunset and look for Yooperlites! To find Yooperlites, you'll need a UV flashlight.

I wanted to do something a little different this year so when I came across Door County’s annual New Year’s Eve Cherry Drop, I just had to see it for myself! 🍒

We stayed at @loftedpinescottage and oh my goodness... this was just the loveliest little place 🥰

📍Lofted Pines Cottage | Sister Bay, Wisconsin (@loftedpinescottage)
📍The Cherry Drop | Sister Bay, Wisconsin

The location of Lofted Pines was exactly what I was looking for. It was tucked down a quiet road surrounded by trees yet only a 6-minute drive to downtown Sister Bay. It was so nice to be close to all the festivities but I also loved being able to retreat somewhere quiet and peaceful.

We kicked off the night with the Sister Bay fireworks show at 8pm at the Teresa K. Hilander Community Ice Rink. It was about a 20-minute show.

Afterwards, we had a late dinner reservation at CHOP. This steak house is right in the heart of Sister Bay and has a nice ambience inside. If you want to try a fun cocktail with a unique flavor combination, get the Passionfruit Jalapeño Margarita. Tip: book your NYE dinner reservation as early as possible since they fill up fast! I used Open Table. If they’re booked, check back frequently to see if any spots opened up.

Then it was time for the famous Door County Cherry Drop! Walk over to Husby’s to see the sparkling 300-pound cherry slowly descend at midnight.

1. Door Bluff Headlands County Park, Door County, WI: Turquoise-colored water and an otherworldly cedar forest. Check out my pinned reel to see more! 
2. Ballard Lake, Star Lake, WI: The cool thing about this lake? There’s a secret channel that you can paddle through to get to another lake! 
3. Pilot Island Lighthouse, Door County, WI: An abandoned lighthouse on a island. The island itself closed to the public but you can see it by boat. It’s eerie! 
4. Corrigan’s Lookout, Saxon, WI: A short, quarter-mile hike will lead you to a rocky outcropping that offers a spectacular panoramic view of Wisconsin’s landscape. I have a blog post about this spot!  
5. Kelley Castle, Tomahawk, WI: A castle on private property open to the public for only one weekend in September each year! Search for the event on Facebook. If you miss it, you’ll have to wait another year. 
6. Mountain Fire Lookout Tower, Mountain, WI: One of the few remaining fire towers in Wisconsin where visitors can climb to the top. 
7. Observatory Hill, Marquette County, WI: A short, 0.6-mile out and back hike. When you reach the top, you’ll be treated to a stunning view of Marquette County. Read my Marquette Co. blog post for more info. 
8. Bittersweet Lakes State Natural Area, Woodruff, WI: Often referred to as a “mini Boundary Waters”, here you’ll find a series of four small lakes with four short portages in between and with five primitive, reservable campsites. I posted a reel about this spot with more info!

A few of my favorites ❤️ if you have questions about any of these places, let me know in the comments!
